## HLD vs LLD: The Abstraction Ladder
The Harness article describes the SDLC Design phase as a single step, but the testRigor analysis breaks it into two critical layers: [lilys](https://lilys.ai/en/notes/ai-coding-agents-20251225/claude-code-ai-agent-guide)

- **HLD (High-Level Design)**: System architecture, module relationships, technology stack, data flows. Audience: architects, stakeholders. Answers **"what"** the system does.
- **LLD (Low-Level Design)**: Classes, methods, algorithms, data structures. Audience: developers, testers. Answers **"how"** the system does it.

The C4 Model refines this further into four zoom levels: System Context → Container → Component → Code. Each level serves a different audience and a different decision point. [visual-c4](https://www.visual-c4.com/blog/4-cluster-understanding-c4-model-levels)

The critical insight from the testRigor article: **the flow is bidirectional**. Discoveries during LLD can force HLD changes. Your workflow already handles this — if an Implementer discovers a module boundary violation, it's a Tier 3 escalation back to the Architect. [ppl-ai-file-upload.s3.amazonaws](https://ppl-ai-file-upload.s3.amazonaws.com/web/direct-files/attachments/64120149/2b69e660-c251-4975-8a51-ad1b684eab2c/WORKFLOW.md)
## Mapping Your Workflow to Abstraction Levels
Here's the core framework: each workflow phase operates at a specific abstraction level, and should load **only the context appropriate to that level**.
| Workflow Phase | Abstraction Level | C4 Level | Context to Load | Context to EXCLUDE |
|---------------|-------------------|----------|-----------------|-------------------|
| Intake + Architecture | HLD (System) | 1-2 | ARCHITECTURE.md, DECISIONS.md, V1_PLAN.md | Source code, test files |
| Design Options + Eval | HLD → LLD | 2-3 | Above + contracts, module APIs | Internal implementations |
| Task Shaping | LLD (Component) | 3 | Contracts, file tree, test structure | Architecture docs, vision |
| Implementation + VBR | Code | 4 | In-scope files ONLY + tests | Architecture, plan, use cases |
| Review | LLD + Code | 3-4 | Git diff, acceptance criteria, rules | Full architecture docs |
| Capture & Close | HLD (System) | 1-2 | DECISIONS.md, PROGRESS.md, git log | Source code, tests |
## Why Context Scoping Matters for AI
Anthropic's own research on context engineering confirms your instinct. Three key findings: [anthropic](https://www.anthropic.com/engineering/effective-context-engineering-for-ai-agents)

1. **Context rot is real**: As tokens increase, the model's ability to recall information degrades. It's not a hard cliff but a performance gradient — more tokens means less precision. [anthropic](https://www.anthropic.com/engineering/effective-context-engineering-for-ai-agents)
2. **Minimal relevant context wins**: Chkk's research shows "less but sharper beats more but messy every single time" — dumping your entire codebase into a prompt is like forwarding your intern every email since 2018. [chkk](https://www.chkk.io/blog/your-ai-agent-needs-minimal-relevant-context-at-the-right-time)
3. **Progressive disclosure**: Rather than pre-loading everything, let agents discover context through exploration — each interaction yields context that informs the next decision. [anthropic](https://www.anthropic.com/engineering/effective-context-engineering-for-ai-agents)

The practical failure mode: during Phase 6 (Implementation), if the agent still has ARCHITECTURE.md in context from Phase 2, it may **re-litigate settled architecture decisions** instead of writing code. Anthropic calls this "anchoring on historical context". [chkk](https://www.chkk.io/blog/your-ai-agent-needs-minimal-relevant-context-at-the-right-time)
## The Anti-Pattern Your USE_CASES.md Exposes
Your USE_CASES.md is 55,616 characters. Loading it into every interaction would consume roughly 40% of a typical context window. But during Implementation (Phase 6), the agent only needs to know it's implementing **NF-01** — not read 35 use cases. The fix is referencing by ID (`"This task implements NF-01"`) rather than loading the full document. [anthropic](https://www.anthropic.com/engineering/effective-context-engineering-for-ai-agents)
